[ORIGINAL Article 51]
Article 51
The Visit Stay Permit ends because the Visit Stay Permit holder:
a. return to their home country;
b. the permit has expired;
c. izinnya beralih status menjadi Izin Tinggal terbatas;
d. izinnya dibatalkan oleh Menteri atau Pejabat Imigrasi yang ditunjuk;
e. dikenai Deportasi; or
f. die.

---

[ORIGINAL Article 141]
Article 141
When this Law comes into force:
a. Visit Stay Permits, limited Stay Permits and Permanent Stay Permits issued based on Law Number 9 of 1992 concerning Immigration are declared to remain valid until their term ends;
b. husband or wife of a legal marriage with an Indonesian citizen whose marriage is more than 2 (two) years old and holds a limited Stay Permit based on Law Number 9 of 1992 concerning Immigration can immediately be granted a Permanent Stay Permit according to the provisions of this Law;
c. Republic of Indonesia Travel Documents that have been issued based on Law Number 9 of 1992 concerning Immigration are declared to remain valid until their term expires; and
d. Criminal cases in the Immigration sector that are currently being processed at the investigation stage are still being processed based on the Law on Criminal Procedure Law.

---

[ORIGINAL Article 55]
Article 55
The granting, extension and cancellation of visit Stay Permits, limited Stay Permits and Permanent Stay Permits is carried out by the Minister or appointed Immigration Official.

---

[ORIGINAL Article 53]
Article 53
The limited Stay Permit expires because the limited Stay Permit holder:
a. returns to his country of origin and does not intend to re-enter Indonesian Territory;
b. return to their country of origin and not return beyond the validity period of their Re-Entry Permit;
c. obtain citizenship of the Republic of Indonesia;
d. the permit has expired;
e. the permit changes status to Permanent Residence Permit;
f. the permit is canceled by the Minister or appointed Immigration Official;
g. subject to deportation; or
h. die.

---

[ORIGINAL Article 62]
Article 62
(1) A Permanent Stay Permit may expire because the Permanent Stay Permit holder:
a. leaving the Indonesian Territory for more than 1 (one) year or not intending to re-enter the Indonesian Territory;
b. not extending the Permanent Stay Permit after 5 (five) years;
c. obtain citizenship of the Republic of Indonesia;
d. the permit is canceled by the Minister or appointed Immigration Official;
e. subject to deportation; or
f. die.
(2) Permanent Stay Permit is canceled because the Permanent Stay Permit holder:
a. proven to have committed a criminal act against the state as regulated in statutory regulations;
b. carrying out activities that endanger state security;
c. violate the Integration Statement;
d. employing foreign workers without work permits;
e. providing incorrect information in applying for a Permanent Residence Permit;
f. The foreigner concerned is subject to Immigration Administrative Action; or
g. termination of the marriage relationship of foreigners who are legally married to Indonesian citizens due to divorce and/or based on a court decision, except for marriages that are 10 (ten) years old or more.

[ORIGINAL Article 78]
Article 78
(1) Foreigners holding a Stay Permit whose validity period has expired and are still in the Indonesian Territory for less than 60 (sixty) days from the Stay Permit deadline are subject to a burden fee in accordance with the provisions of statutory regulations.
(2) Foreigners who do not pay the fees as intended in paragraph (1) are subject to Immigration Administrative Action in the form of Deportation and Detention.
(3) Foreigners holding a Stay Permit whose validity period has expired and are still in Indonesian Territory for more than 60 (sixty) days from the Stay Permit deadline are subject to Immigration Administrative Action in the form of Deportation and Detention.

---

[ORIGINAL Article 122]
Article 122
Sentenced to a maximum imprisonment of 5 (five) years and a maximum fine of Rp. 500,000,000.00 (five hundred million rupiah):
a. any Foreigner who deliberately misuses or carries out activities that are not in accordance with the aims and objectives of the Stay Permit granted to him;
b. any person who orders or provides an opportunity for a Foreigner to abuse or carry out activities that are not in accordance with the aim or purpose of granting the Stay Permit given to him.

---

[ORIGINAL Article 62]
Article 62
(1) A Permanent Stay Permit may expire because the Permanent Stay Permit holder:
a. leaving the Indonesian Territory for more than 1 (one) year or not intending to re-enter the Indonesian Territory;
b. not extending the Permanent Stay Permit after 5 (five) years;
c. obtain citizenship of the Republic of Indonesia;
d. the permit is canceled by the Minister or appointed Immigration Official;
e. subject to deportation; or
f. die.
(2) Permanent Stay Permit is canceled because the Permanent Stay Permit holder:
a. proven to have committed a criminal act against the state as regulated in statutory regulations;
b. carrying out activities that endanger state security;
c. violate the Integration Statement;
d. employing foreign workers without work permits;
e. providing incorrect information in applying for a Permanent Residence Permit;
f. The foreigner concerned is subject to Immigration Administrative Action; or
g. termination of the marriage relationship of foreigners who are legally married to Indonesian citizens due to divorce and/or based on a court decision, except for marriages that are 10 (ten) years old or more.

---

[ORIGINAL Article 123]
Article 123
Sentenced to a maximum imprisonment of 5 (five) years and a maximum fine of Rp. 500,000,000.00 (five hundred million rupiah):
a. any person who deliberately provides false or falsified documents or data or incorrect information with the intention of obtaining a Visa or Residence Permit for himself or another person;
b. every Foreigner who deliberately uses a Visa or Stay Permit as intended in letter a to enter and/or reside in Indonesian Territory.

---

[ORIGINAL Article 63]
Article 63
(1) Certain Foreigners residing in Indonesian Territory are required to have a Guarantor who guarantees their existence.
(2) The Guarantor is responsible for the whereabouts and activities of the guaranteed Foreigner while staying in Indonesian Territory and is obliged to report any changes in civil status, Immigration status and change of address.
(3) The Guarantor is obliged to pay the costs incurred to repatriate or remove the Foreigner he guarantees from Indonesian Territory if the Foreigner concerned:
a. the validity period of the Stay Permit has expired; and/or
b. subject to Immigration Administrative Action in the form of Deportation.
(4) Provisions regarding guarantees do not apply to foreigners who are legally married to Indonesian citizens.
(5) The provisions as intended in Article 62 paragraph (2) letter g do not apply in the event that the holder of a Permanent Stay Permit terminates his marriage relationship with an Indonesian citizen and obtains a guarantee that guarantees his existence as intended in paragraph (1).

[DEFINITION FROM Article 62]
Article 62
(1) A Permanent Stay Permit may expire because the Permanent Stay Permit holder:
a. leaving the Indonesian Territory for more than 1 (one) year or not intending to re-enter the Indonesian Territory;
b. not extending the Permanent Stay Permit after 5 (five) years;
c. obtain citizenship of the Republic of Indonesia;
d. the permit is canceled by the Minister or appointed Immigration Official;
e. subject to deportation; or
f. die.
(2) Permanent Stay Permit is canceled because the Permanent Stay Permit holder:
a. proven to have committed a criminal act against the state as regulated in statutory regulations;
b. carrying out activities that endanger state security;
c. violate the Integration Statement;
d. employing foreign workers without work permits;
e. providing incorrect information in applying for a Permanent Residence Permit;
f. The foreigner concerned is subject to Immigration Administrative Action; or
g. termination of the marriage relationship of foreigners who are legally married to Indonesian citizens due to divorce and/or based on a court decision, except for marriages that are 10 (ten) years old or more.
